Believers in free trade
- Cambridge - I was recently invited to guest lecture in a globalization course run by two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you,"
one of them cautioned me beforehand: "These students are strong supporters of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and more than 90 percent chose the former.
And this before we even began to teach the magic effect of comparative advantage.
We know that a genuine survey asking representative samples — not Harvard students — the same questions would yield a very different result.
In the U.S., the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students do not come as a surprise.
Because those with higher technical skills and better education tend to be more supportive of free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their (financial) prospects and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they actually don't understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately asked the same question in a different form and emphasized the distributive effects that trade might produce.
The consensus in favor of fair trade disappeared almost completely, even more quickly than I anticipated.
To begin with, I asked everyone whether they agreed that I would conduct a particularly magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers, and told them that I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas's account disappear—poof—and simultaneously increase John's account by $300, with social engineering making this class as a whole worth an additional $100.
Will they allow me to play this little trick?
The result was that only a small part firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed the implementation of this shift.

Clearly, students cannot tolerate such a large-scale form of income redistribution, even when the size of the economic pie has increased.
I then asked why, among them, most people almost instinctively support free trade, which actually leads to a similar – and in fact even more extensive – wealth redistribution from losers to winners.
Students looked stunned.
I continued, let's assume that Nicholas and John both started competing small companies.
John worked harder, saved more, invested more, and produced better products, so he not only had $300 more than Nicholas, but also drove the latter's company out of the market and cost it $200.
How many students favored this outcome?
This time, most voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
Is John挤出市场的办法是通过从德国进口高质量产品？
还是将业务流程外包给劳工权益尚不完善的中国？
抑或是在印度尼西亚雇佣童工？
This time, the degree of agreement with the shift decreases sequentially with these options.
Moreover, technological innovation will also lead to some people being in a more disadvantaged position like trade does, what is your stance on this?
Very few students are willing to restrain the development of technology.
To almost everyone, it is a ridiculous idea to ban the production of light bulbs just to keep candle makers employed.
Therefore, students oppose redistribution not necessarily, but certain forms of it.
Like most of us, they also care about the fairness of the system.
If we are to judge the results of reallocation, we must know the objective environment that produced these results.
We do not resent Bill Gates or Warren Buffett for their vast wealth, even if some of their competitors have had it tough for a long time, likely because both they and their competitors operate under the same basic rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become wealthy through fraud, violating labor laws, destroying the environment, or leveraging foreign government subsidies, our attitudes would be quite different.
If we cannot tolerate reallocation achieved through violations of commonly accepted moral standards within our country, how can we feel comfortable about it when it involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect reallocation effects to lead to greater equality over the long term and believe that everyone will ultimately benefit, we are unlikely to worry too much about the transfer of income.
This is why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative impacts on some individuals, we still support its development.
On the other hand, when trade constantly impacts the same group of people — low-skilled blue-collar workers — we worry about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious distinctions.
They tend to attribute concerns about globalization to foolish and selfish protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most crucial issue is actually moral.
Unable to recognize that international trade sometimes — of course not always — leads to redistributive consequences that we would not accept domestically, these economists cannot properly engage in public discourse.
And if their arguments on moral grounds are untenable, how can they defend trade vigorously?
When globalization occasionally raises a tricky issue related to the legalization of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond by restricting trade.
There are many pros and cons to carefully weigh, including the possibility that globalization may deprive people elsewhere of wealth more severely than it does American victims.
But democratic nations should have a more appropriate discussion on this and make conscious and more considered decisions.
A fixation on globalization simply because it has made the pie bigger will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long run.
